echnological artefacts as a necessary entry point for understanding the meanings and politics of children’s digital play. The discussion draws on several research studies on a wide range of digital playgrounds designed and marketed to children aged six to twelve years, revealing how various problematic tendencies prevent most digital play spaces from effectively supporting children’s culture, rights, and – ironically – play. Digital Playgrounds lays the groundwork for a critical reconsideration of how existing approaches might be used in the development of new regulation, as well as best practices for the industries involved in making children’s digital play spaces. In so doing, it argues that children’s online play spaces be reimagined as a crucial new form of public sphere in which children’s rights and digital citizenship must be prioritized.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aChildren's software. 0aComputer gamesxSocial aspects. 0aComputers and children. 0aInternet gamesxSocial aspects. 0aPlay. 0aShared virtual environmentsxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  achildren’s content.  achildren’s games.  achildren’s play.  achildren’s privacy.  achildren’s rights online.  acommercialization of childhood.  aconnected games.  acultural industries.  adigital play.  agaming.  aonline games.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266819540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442668195423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442668195/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles